<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
(Female): Type locality. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Brazil</emphasis>
, Amazonas, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tefé">Tefe</normalizedToken>
(Ega) (MHNP).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
Azadeh Taghavian at the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Muséum">Museum</normalizedToken>
national 
<normalizedToken originalValue="d’Histoire">d'Histoire</normalizedToken>
naturelle in Paris was unable to locate the specimen amongst the Mateu collection. Therefore, we believe the type has been lost and a neotype will be needed when additional specimens are found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="derivation of specific epithet">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Derivation of specific epithet.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
The epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mateu" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Straneotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Straneotia amazonica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Straneotia amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a singular Latin feminine noun in apposition referring to the macrohabitat in which the holotype was found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="proposed english vernacular name">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Proposed English Vernacular Name.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Amazon slim arboreal carabid.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="75" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="75">
With the attributes of the genus and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mateu" authorityYear="1961" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Straneotia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Straneotia amazonica" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="75">Straneotia amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group as described above and adults without a flared post-lateral margin of the pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
